{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}} {{Use Indian English|date=September 2017}}
[[File:Kohbar of Mithila.png|thumbnail|right|200px|Kohbar made by artist Padma Shri Sita Devi.]] '''Madhubani art''' (or '''Mithila painting''') is practiced in the [[Mithila (region)|Mithila region]] of the [[Indian subcontinent]]. Painting is done with fingers, twigs, brushes, nib-pens, and matchsticks, etc. using natural dyes and pigments, and is characterised by eye-catching geometrical patterns.{{cn|date=September 2018}} There is ritual content for particular occasions, such as birth or marriage, and festivals, such as [[Holi]], Surya Shasti, [[kali puja|Kali Puja]], [[Upanayana]], [[Durga Puja]].
== Origins== Madhubani art or Mithila painting was traditionally created by the women of various communities in [[Mithila (ancient)|Mithila]] region of the Indian subcontinent. It originated from [[Madhubani district]] of Mithila region of [[Bihar]], and, it is popularly called Mithila painting or Madhubani art. Madhubani is also a major export centre of these paintings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=UvuJyvtsCjwC&pg=PA96&dq=madhubani+art+madhubani+district&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj8kJ761p_SAhUrIsAKHb2ZDfYQ6AEIIzAC#v=onepage&q=madhubani+art+madhubani+district&f=false|title=Madhubani Painting|date=30 September 2017|publisher=Abhinav Publications|via=Google Books|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170221110108/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=UvuJyvtsCjwC&pg=PA96&dq=madhubani+art+madhubani+district&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj8kJ761p_SAhUrIsAKHb2ZDfYQ6AEIIzAC#v=onepage&q=madhubani+art+madhubani+district&f=false|archivedate=21 February 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This painting as a form of wall art was practiced widely throughout the region; the more recent development of painting on paper and canvas mainly originated among the villages around Madhubani, and it is these latter developments led to the name ''Madhubani art'' being used alongside the name "Mithila Painting."<ref>Carolyn Brown Heinz, 2006, "Documenting the Image in Mithila Art," Visual Anthropology Review, Vol. 22, Issue 2, pp. 5-33</ref>
The painting was traditionally done on freshly plastered mud walls and floors of huts, but now they are also done on cloth, handmade paper and [[canvas]].<ref name=krupa>{{cite news|last=Krupa|first=Lakshmi|title=Madhubani walls|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/homes-and-gardens/madhubani-walls/article4272411.ece|accessdate=5 February 2014|newspaper=The Hindu|date=4 January 2013|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140129100902/http://www.thehindu.com/features/homes-and-gardens/madhubani-walls/article4272411.ece|archivedate=29 January 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Madhubani paintings are made from the paste of powdered rice. Madhubani painting has remained confined to a compact geographical area and the skills have been passed on through centuries, the content and the style have largely remained the same. And that is the reason for Madhubani painting being accorded the coveted GI ([[Geographical Indication]]) status. Madhubani paintings also use two-dimensional imagery, and the colors used are derived from plants. [[Ochre]] and [[lampblack]] are also used for reddish brown and black respectively.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}
Madhubani paintings mostly depict the men & its association with nature and the scenes & deity from the ancient epics. Natural objects like the sun, the moon, and religious plants like [[tulsi]] are also widely painted, along with scenes from the royal court and social events like weddings. Generally, no space is left empty; the gaps are filled by paintings of flowers, animals, birds, and even geometric designs.{{citation needed|date=February 2014}} Traditionally, painting was one of the skills that was passed down from generation to generation in the families of the Mithila Region, mainly by women.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://india.gov.in/knowindia/madhubani.php|title=Know India: Madhubani Painting|publisher=India.gov.in|accessdate=2013-09-21|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110907150703/http://india.gov.in/knowindia/madhubani.php|archivedate=7 September 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It is still practiced and kept alive in the institutions spread across Mithila region. [[Kalakriti]]<ref>https://encrypted.google.com/maps/place/Kalakriti,+mithila+painting+store/@26.16902,85.895148,15z/data=!4m2!3m1!1s0x0:0x22e7e9059046e00e?hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwji4L-ii7TaAhXIqY8KHeLcDIQQ_BIIgQEwDw {{dead link|date=September 2017}}</ref> in Darbhanga,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wikimapia.org/11525853/Kalakriti-Mithila-painting|title=Kalakriti Mithila painting - Wikimapia|website=wikimapia.org|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510121515/http://wikimapia.org/11525853/Kalakriti-Mithila-painting|archivedate=10 May 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Vaidehi in Madhubani, Benipatti in Madhubani district and Gram Vikas Parishad in Ranti are some of the major centers of Madhubani painting which has kept this ancient art form alive. {{citation needed|date=September 2017}} [[File:Krishna & Radha made by Sita devi.jpg|thumbnail|Krishna & Radha made by Sita Devi|200px]]
== Styles == Madhubani art has five distinctive styles, namely, Bharni, Katchni, Tantrik, Godna and Kohbar. In the 1960s Bharni, Kachni and Tantrik style were mainly done by Brahman and Kayashth women, who are 'upper caste' women in India and Nepal. Their themes were mainly religious and they depicted Gods and Goddesses, flora and fauna in their paintings. People of lower castes include aspects of their daily life and symbols, story of Raja Shailesh [ guard of village] and much more, in their paintings. But nowadays Madhubani art has become a globalised art form so there is no difference in the work of artists of the region on the basis of the caste system. They are working in all five styles. Madhubani art has received worldwide attention.<ref name="a-painter-from-patna-crafted-a-live-madhubani-painting-in-bangkok/">{{cite web|url=https://www.atulyabihar.com/a-painter-from-patna-crafted-a-live-madhubani-painting-in-bangkok/ |title=a-painter-from-patna-crafted-a-live-madhubani-painting-in-bangkok</ref>
== Artists and awards == Madhubani painting received official recognition in 1969 when [[Sita Devi (painter)|Sita Devi]] received the State award by Government of Bihar. In 1975, President of India gave the [[Padma Shri]] award to Jagdamba Devi, and the National Award to Sita Devi of Jitwarpur village near Madhubani.<ref name="Padma Shri">{{cite web|url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |title=Padma Shri |publisher=Padma Shri |date=2015 |accessdate=11 November 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6U68ulwpb?url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |archivedate=15 November 2014 |df= }}</ref> Sita Devi received the Padma Shri in 1981. Sita Devi was also awarded by Bihar Ratna in 1984 and [[Shilp Guru]] in 2006. In 1984 [[Ganga Devi (painter)|Ganga Devi]] <ref name="Ganga Devi: Tradition and expression in Madhubani painting">{{cite journal | url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/09528828908576213?journalCode=ctte20#.Ve-1rvmSxAA | title=Ganga Devi: Tradition and expression in Madhubani painting | author=Jyotindra Jain | journal=Taylor and Francis Online | year=1989 | volume=3 | issue=6 | doi=10.1080/09528828908576213}}</ref> was awarded by Padma Shri.<ref name="Padma Awards">{{cite web|url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |title=Padma Awards |publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India |date=2015 |accessdate=21 July 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6U68ulwpb?url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |archivedate=15 November 2014 |df= }}</ref> [[Mahasundari Devi]] received the Padma Shri in 2011. Bauwa Devi, Yamuna Devi, Shanti Devi, Chano Devi, Bindeshwari Devi, Chandrakala Devi, Shashi kala Devi, Leela Devi, Godavari Dutta, and [[Bharti Dayal]] were also given the National award.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=9EtXTa_7FcOBlAetnrSuBw&ct=result&id=huLqAAAAMAAJ&dq=Madhubani+painting&q=1970#search_anchor |title=Madhubani painting – Upendra Thakur – Google Boeken |publisher=Books.google.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-21}}</ref><ref name=living>{{cite news|last=Tripathi|first=Shailaja|title=Madhubani beyond the living rooms|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/events/madhubani-beyond-the-living-rooms/article5380171.ece|accessdate=3 February 2014|newspaper=The HIndu|date=22 November 2013|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140131165843/http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/events/madhubani-beyond-the-living-rooms/article5380171.ece|archivedate=31 January 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/art-that-subverts/article5059973.ece|title=Art that subverts|date=26 August 2013|publisher=|via=www.thehindu.com|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130826090447/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/art-that-subverts/article5059973.ece|archivedate=26 August 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Chandrabhushan, Ambika Devi, Manisha jha were also given the National award.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}
